AB  - Hypertension in type 1 diabetes mellitus, which is an interdisciplinary topic, concerning both cardiology and diabetology, which are both internal medicine branches, is a highly topical concept. There are two aspects that seem to play an essential role in the ethical approach of such a patient: diagnosis communication and therapeutic approach. A "highly paternalistic" approach - which is extremely controversial and which would violate the patient's right of making his/her own decisions - does not meet the requirements of a long-term compliance. Accepting a chronic condition depends on the best balance between the doctor's and the patient's responsibilities, as these two are in a partnership relation. The partnership approach used on patients has left tradition behind and has made room for the increasingly frequent central concept called patient autonomy. Disputes occur when autonomous patients refuse the treatment. The final goal is a successful disease management and self-management. This is possible only when the patient is willing to accept his/her medical background, to understand why it is important for him/her to change his/her lifestyle and to observe the strictest therapy plan, although this is unable to cure him/her, although, despite our efforts as doctors, we do not have a healing solution. Another issue is the social impact - the society's attitude towards these patients, who are also "chronic consumers of partially free and fully free prescriptions". Therefore, these people, who actually have a normal social behavior, often end up stigmatized and marginalized. All these dilemmas and controversies, in addition to social prejudice and myth, and to patient stigmatization, clearly prove that patients suffering from such an association of diagnoses are more than a simply medical management challenge. They are actually a real approach challenge.
