AB  - For Jews, antisemitism is something concretely expressed. There are antisemitic words, antisemitic pictures, antisemitic statements, etc. Whether the person is or isn't an antisemite “in his heart” is irrelevant…. We need only look at what he or she has said or written. An ontological state of “being an anti-Semite” is not a necessary condition either for being able to say something antisemitic or for having to be responsible for what one has said (Wolkoff, 1992; author's translation).Starting from everyday hostility, this paper moves to the differences between ideas and xenophobic prejudices. A clinical vignette leads to a discussion of orthodoxy and fundamentalism and the general human tendency to regard certain other people as “my own team” different to others. This is further emphasized in the image of immigrants, where latent hatred is easily aroused; this is especially true in the case of everyday myths and prejudices in antisemitism, where the “perverse” thoughts and regressive group dynamics are involved to a great extent. The combination of authoritarian socialization and an undemocratic view of society is deadly. So is our never-ending tendency to fall back on splitting and projection of unwanted sides of ourselves. Sufficiently safe people in well-organized groups with democratically elected, non-sadistic leaders do not commit violent crimes based on prejudices and fantasies of revenge. © 2010, Taylor & Francis Group, LLC. All rights reserved.
